metadata.name: When we were Kids #5
metadata.description:
When we were kids.

A work that goes back to our childhood.
When I was a kid I loved spending time with my grandmother and parents, we took a lot of walks with them, looked at different houses, spent time in nature, painted and in general were very much involved in the creative component, it was my parents and grandmother who instilled in me a love for creativity.

Probably one of the few things that have survived to these days is my childhood drawings, a little funny, sloppy, but so real and sincere.

In this work I wanted to take me back to those carefree times and remember with what eagerness and zeal I tried every day to learn something new or to go further than before.

None of this would have happened without my family, for which I am truly grateful.

10% of primary sales will be donated to Cure Parkinson's, I hope all children will have a childhood where they can spend time with their loved ones.

Be patient, some variations take a little longer to render.

Press S for Save Canvas as PNG.

By aleks.ustya, @ALEKUSTN. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Sketches:Pairs of Tails:Majestic Creatures #29
metadata.description:
Addendum to Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

There is a significantly common phenomena in which Pairs of "Tails of Majestic Creatures" are found together. Various sketches of these "Pairs" have been collated and are available, free of charge, the collectors of the initial Tails of Majestic Creatures collection based upon a recently taken collection registry snapshot. 

These sketches are available on a one per collector basis and for a limited time only after which they will no longer be accessible.

The sketches come in 2 forms - an ink and color style, and a pencil style - for which different colored paper has been used.

The digitally minded can press s to get a 5000x3000 download of a sketch.

metadata.name: Konstruktion v0.5 #70
metadata.description:
Further exploration of mathematical beauty and chaos combining to build an elemental konstruktion in space. It started a few weeks ago as a vague concept in my mind, leading to the development of a unique form that transcends normal design.

Every generated piece is so unique that I cannot conceive of a feature or classification system. Please enjoy the beauty of this creation!

Release v0.5 is limited to screen resolution save (using "s" or "S" as described below). If you're interested in high-resolution images, please consider release v1.0.

All proceeds shared with Three.js and Girls Who Code.

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle

With the keyboard:

The "f" key will freeze the animation entirely. This can be used if you want to save the image at a specific viewpoint.

Keys "," and "." (or "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed.

Key "s" will save to a ".png" file at screen resolution.
Key "S" will save to a ".jpg" file at screen resolution.

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #913
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”

metadata.name: Crayons - v2 #29
metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Crayons was originally published as Project #5746 on January 5, 2022.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/5746)
Due to a technical issue, Project #5746 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________

This art aims to remember the traces of crayons scratching blackboards and even walls, if you prefer. In a child's hands, a crayon represents freedom to draw whatever he wants, even if it's an indefinite scribble. And with these scribbles, I bring to this code the straight, horizontal and vertical lines, which intersect, always mixing two palettes, thus obtaining a perception of incredible depth and texture.

Carefully chosen color palettes.

FEATURES:
> Crayons Amount 🖍: 300 to 1100.
> Vertical Crayons Palette 🎨: Education levels.
> Horizontal Crayons Palette 🎨: Education levels.
> Classroom Blackboard Color ⬛️: Somethings to study.
> Color Effect¹: Normal ★, Negative Mode ★★ or GrayScale Mode ★★★.

RARITY BONUS:
> (★) = rarity level: ★ = 85%, ★★ = 15%, ★★★ = 5%.
> If you got ★★ or ★★★, you will discover

INTERACTIVE MODS, PRESS ANYTIME:
> "P" to pause/play.
> "S" to save a .png of your canvas (in Open Live).
> "N" to switch the Negative, if you got one.
> "G" to switch the GrayScale, if you got one.

Made with p5.js

_______________________________

metadata.name: I Stockpile Dreams With Tragedies : 2Gen #27
metadata.description:
"I Stockpile Dreams With Tragedies : 2Gen" is an experimental generative art piece that is an attempt to highlight some of the inherent contradictions surrounding the discussion of non-fungible tokens (NFTs) and its place as a vehicle for artistic creation, artistic expression and the potential of remuneration for artists.

p - pause

s - screenshot

a - (advanced) record animation (5s)

To the extent possible, the source code is dedicated to the public domain (CC0) and can be used for any purpose, even commercial, by anyone. Third party libraries are used that are not CC0 licensed but have libre/free licensing terms that allow for commercial reuse (please see the LICENSE section for more details).

This work is influenced by stock art that is available from pay-to-download sites as well as drawing influence from other artists that have similar styles but don't make their art, or the code to generate it, libre/free.

Many times stock image sites that make available pictures similar to ones generated by this code can incur costs of $10 or more per image. Many sites offer monthly subscription rates starting at $50 per year. Price gouging, restrictive licensing and overly broad copyright terms are taken as the norm while technology that experiments with ideas of uniqueness, value and enabling alternative income streams is berated.

Why are stock image sites valuable but receiving payments from NFTs not?

"I Stockpile Dreams With Tragedies : 2Gen" is a continuation of "I Stockpile Dreams With Tragedies" incorporating additional basic shapes, shape selection and color.

This work hopes to add to the conversation about examining the reality of the ecosystem that we've developed around digital goods and intellectual property.

metadata.name: Prospettive Astratte - Floating structures #14
metadata.description:
Perspective and abstraction, generates 3D a structure, a grid of floating objects projected in perspective, in some cases a close up detail. Sometime close to a regular pattern, sometime more chaotic like any urban development. 
Inside complex generated textures, based on a colored palette tanke from a Leonardo Da Vinci and Botticelli painting

By either MOUSE CLICKING over the canvas or touching it, color palette will redistribute over the *same* token shape, as well transparency will be affected. This could give the effect of a changing shape, while instead are hidden shapes "re-emerging" from transparency, while other may disappear.

metadata.name: Tranquility #93
metadata.description:
There was an original meaning to this piece, but it washed away over time, nevertheless Tranquility is a representation of the challenges of connecting to others and the resilience required to navigate the complexity of human relationships. Tranquility features sharp and dynamic lines that result in intricate and often chaotic patterns (conveying the intensity and complexity of the human experience).

Generative artwork - www.petitsapin.com
Press "s" in live view to download high-res version.

metadata.name: Feedback Splash (interactive) #48
metadata.description:
Control a shape that emanates a range of colorful trails of feedback! Fill the canvas in a few seconds with your unique chunks of colors and use the mouse position* to rotate & displace them as you please to rearrange the ever-changing patterns.

*Horizontal mouse position controls rotation.

Press 's' in Live View window ("open live") to save a PNG from your canvas. 

Free to use as you wish! You can create derivatives, use as a collage element or sell as is - your creativity is the limit. Use your shapes and colors wisely!
Tag me so I can see your creations

@bernizeck
2021

Variable features:
Different color values (the closer to B&W, the rarer)
Different shapes (triangles and squares are uncommon)
Dampening factor in cursor control over displacement (+ clockwise or counterclockwise motion)
Feedback trail main direction (w/o cursor influence)
Feedback trail displacement factor (influences speed of displacement)

Special thanks to @AlexandreRangel for the help with the "save as PNG" functionality.
